The Oratoire du Louvre was originally a royal chapel, located extremely close to the Louvre.   It was given to the protestants by Napoleon. It is one of the few domed churches in Paris.   You can also get into the "boxes" to see how the richer people worshipped.  There is a small yard and monumental sculpture along the Rue de Rivoli.   There is also an upstairs room that is round and has quite dramatic architectural features.

The Protestant Church of the Oratory of the Louvre is one of the most important Protestant church buildings in Paris. It is located near the Louvre and has a rich history dating back to the 17th century.  The Oratoire du Louvre, as it is known in French, was founded in 1611 by the Protestant priest Pierre Fosse. It originally functioned as a house of prayer, but over time it developed into a full church. The current building was constructed between 1621 and 1625.  A notable aspect of the Oratoire du Louvre is its architecture. It belongs to the period of French classicism and was designed by the well-known architect Jacques Lerouin. The style of the building is striking, with classic lines and decorative elements that reflect its era.  Today, the Protestant Church of the Oratory of the Louvre continues to function as a place of worship for the Protestant community of Paris, while also opening its doors for cultural events and exhibitions.

VERY BEAUTIFUL BUILDING, CONSTRUCTION STARTED IN 1616 AND FINISHED IN 1750.  In the 17th century, the Catholic Church sought to react to the Protestant Reformation by reforming itself. The Society of the Oratory of Jesus, founded by Father de Bérulle in 1611, expresses this movement of faith and morality closer to the Gospel. . Marie de Medici, then regent of France, declared the congregation of the Oratory a royal foundation on January 2, 1612.  ART RESIDENCE
